\begin{METHODS}
1. **Resolution and Aliasing Convergence Study**: Execute a comparative study between the $512^3$ and $1024^3$ mesh resolutions using a fixed $512^3$ particle set. For the $1024^3$ run, ensure the FFT routines are configured to handle the increased memory footprint. Compare the resulting $P(k)$ at $z=0$ for both resolutions to determine if the power suppression at $k \approx 0.25 \, h/\text{Mpc}$ is mitigated by the finer grid, thereby isolating grid-resolution effects from force-interpolation artifacts.

2. **CIC Window Deconvolution**: Implement a post-processing step to correct for the CIC mass assignment window function. Apply the inverse window function $W^{-2}(k) = [\text{sinc}(k_x \Delta/2) \text{sinc}(k_y \Delta/2) \text{sinc}(k_z \Delta/2)]^{-2}$ to the measured density field in Fourier space before calculating the power spectrum. This correction must be applied to both the $512^3$ and $1024^3$ outputs to ensure the comparison with the Quijote reference is not biased by the mass assignment geometry.

3. **Theoretical PM-Prediction Comparison**: Develop a theoretical model for the PM-expected power spectrum by applying a grid-based force smoothing kernel to the linear theory $P(k)$. Use this as a secondary benchmark alongside the Quijote non-linear reference. This allows for the quantification of the "force softening" effect inherent to the PM algorithm, distinguishing between expected algorithmic behavior and actual simulation errors.

4. **Shot Noise and Variance Analysis**: Re-evaluate the shot noise subtraction by calculating the effective number density $\bar{n}$ directly from the simulation volume and particle count. Perform a variance analysis at low-$k$ ($k < 0.03 \, h/\text{Mpc}$) by comparing the ensemble-averaged power spectrum against the theoretical sample variance expected for a 1000 Mpc/h box. This will determine if the observed low-$k$ residuals are statistically significant or merely a result of cosmic variance within the 10-realization ensemble.

5. **Refined Performance Profiling**: Conduct a granular performance benchmark on the RTX PRO 6000, specifically comparing the $512^3$ and $1024^3$ mesh configurations. Measure the wall-clock time for the FFT and CIC kernels separately to identify the scaling behavior of the Warp implementation. Document the memory overhead and execution time to define the optimal mesh-to-particle ratio for the hardware.

6. **Data Synthesis and Validation**: Compile the corrected $P(k)$ measurements (post-deconvolution) and compare them against the Quijote fiducial data. Calculate the ratio $\langle P_{warp}(k) \rangle / P_{quijote}(k)$ and verify if the 5% agreement target is met across the $k < 0.3 \, h/\text{Mpc}$ range. Use the findings from the resolution study and theoretical PM-prediction to provide a quantitative explanation for any remaining residuals.
\end{METHODS}


